class Solution:
    def canBeEqual(self, s1: str, s2: str) -> bool:
        return sorted([s1[0], s1[2]]) == sorted([s2[0], s2[2]]) and \
               sorted([s1[1], s1[3]]) == sorted([s2[1], s2[3]])


"""
Approach & Reasoning:

The allowed operation swaps characters whose indices differ by 2.
So:
- index 0 can only swap with index 2
- index 1 can only swap with index 3

This means the string is split into two independent groups:
- even positions: {0, 2}
- odd positions: {1, 3}

Within each group, we can freely rearrange the two characters by swapping if needed.
Therefore, s1 can be transformed into s2 if and only if:
- the multiset of characters at positions {0, 2} matches in both strings
- the multiset of characters at positions {1, 3} matches in both strings

So we compare:
- sorted([s1[0], s1[2]]) with sorted([s2[0], s2[2]])
- sorted([s1[1], s1[3]]) with sorted([s2[1], s2[3]])

Time Complexity: O(1)
Space Complexity: O(1)
"""
